":"před 1180–po 1246","1180–1246":"1180–1246","1200–Male":"1200–Zesnulý","1225–1270":"1225–1270","1166–1208":"1166–1208","1165–Female":"1165–Zesnulá","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1200":"1200","1166":"1166","1165":"1165","1270":"1270","1208":"1208","before 1180":"před 1180","after 1246":"po 1246","1180":"1180","England":"Anglie","Holderness, Yorkshire, England":"Holderness, Yorkshire, Anglie"},"da":{"before 1180–after 1246":"før 1180–efter 1246","1180–1246":"1180–1246","1200–Male":"1200–Afdød","1225–1270":"1225–1270","1166–1208":"1166–1208","1165–Female":"1165–Afdød","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1200":"1200","1166":"1166","1165":"1165","1270":"1270","1208":"1208","before 1180":"før 1180","after 1246":"efter 1246","1180":"1180","England":"England","Holderness, Yorkshire, England":"Holderness, Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"before 1180–after 1246":"vóór 1180–na 1246","1180–1246":"1180–1246","1200–Male":"1200–Overleden","1225–1270":"1225–1270","1166–1208":"1166–1208","1165–Female":"1165–Overleden","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1200":"1200","1166":"1166","1165":"1165","1270":"1270","1208":"1208","before 1180":"vóór 1180","after 1246":"na 1246","1180":"1180","England":"England","Holderness, Yorkshire, England":"Holderness, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"before 1180–after 1246":"before 1180–after 1246","1180–1246":"1180–1246","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1225–1270":"1225–1270","1166–1208":"1166–1208","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1200":"1200","1166":"1166","1165":"1165","1270":"1270","1208":"1208","before 1180":"before 1180","after 1246":"after 1246","1180":"1180","England":"England","Holderness, Yorkshire, England":"Holderness, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sutton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called Sutton, named with Old English <i>sūth</i> ‘south, southern’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The English surname is also common in Ireland (Wexford, Kildare), where it has been established since the 13th century and Gaelicized as <b>de Sutún</b>.","Jewish (from the former Ottoman Empire, including Syria): unexplained.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>(bi) suthentune</i> ‘(at the place to the) south of the village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Setton","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avi, Ronit, Yossef.  French Andree, Henri, Jacques, Maryse.","Jewish (from the Ottoman Empire): altered form of   Sutton  .","English (Middlesex): variant of   Seaton  ."]}]},{"name":"Sayer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: common occupational name from Middle English <i>sayer</i>, a phonetic variant of   Sawyer  , which in Wales and neighboring English counties may have been reinforced by the synonymous Welsh <i>saer</i> ‘carpenter’ and everywhere by a possible borrowing into Middle English of Old French <i>seieor</i>, <i>saieur</i> ‘sawyer’.","English: rare occupational name perhaps denoting an assayer of metals, or a servant who tasted his lord's food before serving, from Middle English <i>saiour</i> ‘assayer, tester’ (a shortened form of Old French <i>assaiour</i>, ultimately from Late Latin <i>exagium</i>, a derivative of <i>exagmināre</i> ‘to weigh’).","English: rare occupational name for a professional reciter or minstrel, from Middle English <i>seier(e)</i> ‘speaker’."],"variants":[{"name":"Sayre","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Surrey): variant of   Sayer  ."]},{"name":"Sears","meanings":["Irish (Kerry): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Saoghair</b> ‘son of <i>Saoghar</i>’, a borrowing in Anglo-Norman Ireland of the Anglo-Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Saher</i>, <i>Seier</i> (Old French <i>Seheri</i>), from ancient Germanic <i>Sigeheri</i>, <i>Sighari</i>, composed of the elements <i>sig</i>‘victory’ + <i>hari</i>, <i>heri</i> ‘army’. See   Sayer   5.","English: variant of   Sayers  .","Americanized form of French (or French Canadian)   Cyr   and French <b>Saint-Cyr</b> (see   St. Cyr  ), with the addition of excrescent <i>-s</i>, a common feature of Americanized surnames."]},{"name":"Sear","meanings":["‘peak, crest’, also ‘the best’. Common as an abbreviated form of compound names such as  Chandrasekhar  ‘moon-crested’, an epithet of the god Shiva."]},{"name":"Searson","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Saher</i>, <i>Seier</i> (see   Sayer   5) + <i>-son</i>.","English: variant of <b>Searston</b>, a habitational name from Syerston (Nottinghamshire). The placename probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Sighere</i> (genitive <i>Sigheres</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","Irish (Tipperary): variant of   Sears  ."]},{"name":"Sare","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: apparently from the name of the herb (Middle English <i>sauge</i>, via Old French from Latin <i>salvia</i>);  compare  Sorrel   and   Bay .  In part it may also have been taken from the vocabulary word meaning ‘wise’ (from Latin <i>sapius</i>)."]},{"name":"Saier","meanings":["South German: occupational name for a farmer, from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>saien</i> ‘to sow’. Compare   Sayer   8."]},{"name":"Say","meanings":["Short form of   Raymond  , now also used as an independent given name, especially in North America. In some instances it may represent a transferred use of the surname <i>Ray</i>, which for the most part originated as a nickname, from Old French <i>rei</i>, <i>roi</i> ‘king’ (  compare  Roy   and   Leroy  )."]},{"name":"Sayers","meanings":["English: variant of   Sayer  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This name is also established in Ireland.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Saoghair</b>; see   Sears  ."]},{"name":"Sawyer","meanings":["English: occupational name for someone who earned his living by sawing wood, from Middle English <i>sauer(e)</i>, <i>sauw(i)er</i>, also <i>sagh(i)er</i>, <i>sag(i)er</i> ‘sawyer’, a derivative of Old English <i>sagu</i> ‘saw’.","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname, or translation into English of Jewish   Seger   or some other surname meaning ‘sawyer’, e.g. German   Sager   and Slovenian <b>Žagar</b> (see   Zagar  )."]},{"name":"Seekings","meanings":["English: from the unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Saykin</i>, a pet form of Middle English and Anglo-Norman French <i>Saher</i>, <i>Seier</i> (see   Sayer   5). The final <i>-s</i> is post-medieval and excrescent."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Sayer Sutton was born before 1180, in England, his father, Amandus Sutton, was 11176 and his mother, Jean de Aubigny Albini, was 11176. He had at least 1 son. He died after 1246."},"et":{"before 1180–after 1246":"enne 1180–pärast 1246","1180–1246":"1180–1246","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1225–1270":"1225–1270","1166–1208":"1166–1208","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1246":"1246"